00:01.100 --> 00:14.700
The tape is now on. Okay. In the early to middle 1960s, the so-called new wave
hit science fiction. What did you think of it then, and did it have any

00:14.700 --> 00:29.380
influence on your style? I, to tell you the truth, I was completely confused by
the new wave. It had been going for some time before I was aware of what it was.

00:29.380 --> 00:34.620
I had read some stories that seemed very strange to me.

00:37.440 --> 00:49.260
And then I finally became, you see, I was very well isolated. I was almost,
because I was close to, because I had to keep close to newspaper work, I never

00:49.260 --> 00:57.580
got very far away from home. I was almost never in New York where the real
ferment of all was going on.

01:01.560 --> 01:16.840
But I didn't get as angry or as contemptuous over the new wave as many writers
did. I felt sure that it was just one of the evolutionary things that do happen

01:16.840 --> 01:21.980
occasionally in science fiction, and indeed in any form of literature.

01:25.040 --> 01:42.620
I felt certain that the new wave as such would die out after time. And I hoped
that it would have some beneficial impact on science fiction writing. And in

01:42.620 --> 01:55.960
fact it did. I think that after reading some of the material, especially that
that came out of Britain, that I began to feel that there might be room for

01:55.960 --> 02:07.240
somewhat better writing than some of us have been doing, myself included. And
apparently a number of other people, whether influenced by the new wave or not,

02:08.300 --> 02:23.220
apparently thought the same thing. Because I think that from the time, around
the time the new wave was beginning to die out, that you did begin to see far

02:23.220 --> 02:37.320
more attention to good writing than there had ever been before in the science
fiction field. So, science fiction survived the new wave and benefited from it.

02:37.840 --> 02:47.000
And I suspect that in the years to come, there will be other innovations, other
evolutionary factors

02:47.760 --> 02:57.000
that will be called not new wave, but something else, that may raise a great
deal of controversy, but that science fiction will keep on and probably will

02:57.000 --> 02:58.260
benefit by all of it.

03:01.480 --> 03:17.840
You continue to produce both novels and short stories. I produce very few short
stories, and almost all my time has taken up for a novel. Although I hope that

03:17.840 --> 03:29.900
within the next few years, that I'll be able to write more short stories,
there's nothing quite as satisfactory as writing a good short story. You can't

03:29.900 --> 03:43.760
spend the time, nor the effort, on making a novel shine the way you can make a
short story shine. You can polish it up, you can glean just like a gem. With a

03:43.760 --> 04:03.000
novel, you can't do that. So, I'm pleased, particularly, to see a number of the
magazines hanging in there, because they are giving young writers a chance to

04:03.000 --> 04:11.820
begin their writing career and to polish up the art before they go on to
something longer, into the book market, for example.

04:14.940 --> 04:25.760
When you write, what are the mechanics of your writing? Have you brought a word
processor, or do you still write it out, or type it, or what? I write up my

04:25.760 --> 04:41.540
wrong hand because I, my hand grows slower writing wrong hand than it would on a
typewriter. I write too fast. I get ahead of myself on a typewriter. By writing

04:41.540 --> 04:55.020
wrong hand, I can keep pace with my mind, and I do a better job of writing in
wrong hand. When I finish with, when I've written a few chapters in wrong hand,

04:55.700 --> 05:09.720
by then I run them to the typewriter, making changes and selections and
revisions as I go along, and that is my finished topic. That's the second that's

05:09.720 --> 05:10.360
when I draft.

05:16.260 --> 05:27.020
You've won the major awards, including a very recent one for the short story.
The one I want to ask you about is the Grandmaster Nebula. I would think that it

05:27.020 --> 05:37.280
would be very gratifying to receive an award of this stature from your peers,
not from the fans, but from your peers. That was. I had some. I had never

05:37.280 --> 05:53.660
expected to get it. I was very pleased to get it. It is. It is a recognition of
your standing as an author by the people who themselves are authors. Yes. It

05:53.660 --> 06:10.800
doesn't depend on popularity. It doesn't depend on momentary success. It
depends. It represents a lifetime achievement. and it's rated by people who are

06:11.860 --> 06:23.080
well-qualified to looking at that kind of achievement. It was, I was extremely,
extremely pleased. I'm very proud of it. when you started writing science

06:23.080 --> 06:32.760
fiction in the 1930s, did you dream that your work would last and that your work
in science fiction in general would reach the level of popularity that it seems

06:32.760 --> 06:41.160
to enjoy now? Not at all. Never for a moment. We were working in the ghetto.
There were very few of us.

06:44.420 --> 06:56.320
science fiction was read by only a handful. When you met somebody and they found
out you were a science fiction writer, they'd say, how to get those crazy ideas.

06:57.340 --> 07:00.960
I went thinking around hoping nobody would notice you.

07:03.940 --> 07:18.800
you were the bottom of the heap. There's no question about it. You were much
more despicable within maybe the pornographic letters of today. But we kept at

07:18.800 --> 07:33.940
it because we liked it. Because I think after a few years of it, I began to feel
that probably it would develop and it might have been a science fiction. But I

07:33.940 --> 07:54.160
never dreamed that we would be putting out as great and as good a progress as we
have. A large percentage of the fiction titles that are sold today are science

07:54.160 --> 08:10.680
fiction. And science fiction is beginning to dominate both the movie screen and
television. We are writing the quest of the way and I hope the quest continues

08:10.680 --> 08:12.960
to rise. I see no reason why it shouldn't.

